"""
MKT Context Commentary — Psalms chapters 120–133 (Songs of Ascents, Part 1)
Run: python3 scripts/zc-context-psalms-120-133.py

Source data used:
- data/interlinear/psalms.json
- data/translation/draft/mediating/psalms.json (MKT text)
- data/commentary/ellicott/psalms.json
- data/commentary/jfb/psalms.json

Key decisions in this range:
- Psalms 120-134 are the "Pilgrim Psalter" (maAlot = Songs of Ascents) — 15 psalms
  sung by pilgrims ascending to Jerusalem for the three great pilgrimage festivals
  (Passover, Weeks/Pentecost, Tabernacles — Exod 23:14-17; Deut 16:16).
  Three theories for "ascent": (1) physical uphill road to Jerusalem (elevation ~760m);
  (2) the 15 steps of the Court of Israel in the Temple (Mishnah Middot 2:5);
  (3) the return from Babylonian exile (Ezra 7:9 uses "going up" for the return).
  Staircase parallelism (maAlot-pattern): a word at the end of one verse reappears
  at the start of the next (e.g., Ps 121:3-4 "slumber... slumber/sleep").

- Ps 120: opens with the pilgrim in exile; Meshech/Kedar as merism for "living among
  hostile pagans" — poles of the pagan world used symbolically, not geographically.
  Broom-wood coals (v4) = hottest-burning desert fuel; sustained intense heat.
- Ps 121: "keeper" (shomer) occurs 6x in 8 verses — highest concentration in Psalter;
  the claim that YHWH never sleeps contrasts Baal-mythology and 1 Kgs 18:27.
- Ps 122: Jerusalem unity psalm; wordplay Yerushalayim/shalom almost certainly intentional.
- Ps 123: servant watching master\'s hand = silent ANE household communication.
- Ps 124: "swallowed alive" = chaos-monster imagery (cf. Num 16:30-33 — Korah).
- Ps 126: keholemim ("like dreamers") — the return from Babylon felt unreal.
  Negev wadis = flash-flood imagery of sudden, dramatic restoration.
- Ps 127: attributed to Solomon — the psalm about YHWH as true builder placed
  in the mouth of the man who built the temple; children as legal "arrows" at the gate.
- Ps 130: De profundis — one of seven penitential psalms; Luther\'s "Aus tiefer Not";
  paradox that forgiveness (not wrath) produces awe/reverence.
- Ps 131: weaned child (not nursing infant) = achieved tranquility after crisis, age 2-3.
- Ps 132: royal Davidic covenant psalm; 2 Chr 6:41-42 quotes vv 8-10 at temple
  dedication — this psalm is the liturgical script for that event.
  Ephrathah = Bethlehem; fields of Jaar = Kiriath-jearim (1 Sam 6:21-7:2).
- Ps 133: anointing oil and Hermon-dew as images of fraternal unity;
  "life forever" = eschatological telos of covenant unity at Zion.
"""

import json, pathlib

ROOT = pathlib.Path(__file__).parent.parent

def load_comm(source, book):
    p = ROOT / 'data' / 'commentary' / source / f'{book}.json'
    if p.exists():
        return json.loads(p.read_text())
    return {}

def save_comm(source, book, data):
    p = ROOT / 'data' / 'commentary' / source / f'{book}.json'
    p.parent.mkdir(parents=True, exist_ok=True)
    p.write_text(json.dumps(data, ensure_ascii=False, indent=None))
    print(f'  wrote {p.relative_to(ROOT)}')

def merge_comm(existing, new_data):
    """Merge new_data into existing without overwriting present entries."""
    for ch, verses in new_data.items():
        if ch not in existing:
            existing[ch] = {}
        for v, html in verses.items():
            if v not in existing[ch]:
                existing[ch][v] = html

# INTENT: mkt-context for Psalms 120-133 — the Songs of Ascents pilgrim psalter:
#   journey from exile/foreignness (Ps 120) through trust, arrival, petition,
#   historical thanksgiving (Ps 126), wisdom of divine sovereignty (Ps 127-128),
#   communal lament/penitential depth (Ps 129-130), humility (Ps 131),
#   Davidic covenant (Ps 132), and fraternal unity (Ps 133).
# CHANGE? If commentary/mkt-context/psalms.json structure changes, update load_comm/save_comm.
# VERIFY: python3 -c "import json; d=json.load(open('data/commentary/mkt-context/psalms.json'));
#   [print(ch, len(d[ch])) for ch in ['120','121','122','123','124','125','126','127','128','129','130','131','132','133']]"

PSALMS = {
  "120": {
    "1": '<p>Psalm 120 opens the <em>maAlot</em> collection — fifteen Songs of Ascents (Pss 120-134) sung by pilgrims ascending to Jerusalem for the three great pilgrim festivals: Passover, Weeks (Pentecost), and Tabernacles (Exod 23:14-17; Deut 16:16). The word <em>maAlot</em> (steps, ascents) connects to: (1) the physical ascent of the roads to Jerusalem, which sits at ~760m elevation; (2) the 15 semicircular steps between the Court of Women and the Court of Israel in the temple, on which the Mishnah (Middot 2:5) says the Levites sang these 15 psalms; (3) the "going up" (<em>alah</em>) from Babylonian exile (Ezra 7:9). The collection opens not at Jerusalem but in alienation — the pilgrim\'s starting point is foreignness and slander. The opening cry of distress that receives a divine answer frames the whole pilgrimage: the journey begins in a place where prayer is the only available help, and moves toward the place where prayer finds its home.</p>',
    "2": '<p>"Lying lips and deceitful tongue (<em>lashon remiyyah</em>)" — in the ANE honor-shame social system, verbal warfare was the primary mechanism of social destruction. False accusation, slander in court, perjured testimony, and malicious rumor could strip a person of honor, property, legal standing, and community belonging. The tongue was the weapon most feared because it was hardest to defend against. The Levitical system recognized this urgency: Lev 19:16 forbids slander; Deut 19:16-21 requires that a false witness receive the penalty intended for the accused. The psalmist\'s prayer for rescue from "lying lips" is not merely personal — it is a prayer for the covenant community\'s justice system to operate. The opening of the pilgrimage collection with the problem of the lying tongue situates the whole Psalter of Ascents in the context of an unjust social world from which the pilgrim seeks relief at Zion.</p>',
    "3": '<p>"What will come to you, and what more will be done to you, O deceitful tongue?" — the rhetorical question poses a verdict, which v4 then supplies. The structure is a mock-interrogation of the tongue itself, treating the organ of deception as the defendant in a court proceeding. The psalmist does not threaten personal retaliation — he poses the divine verdict in the form of a question that the deceitful tongue cannot answer, since the nature of the lying tongue is to be silent before the truth it has been evading. In the ancient legal context, the question addressed to the offending party before sentencing was a formal judicial move; the psalmist invokes this court form against the tongue that has wronged him, appealing the case to the divine court.</p>',
    "4": '<p>"A warrior\'s sharp arrows, fired with glowing coals of broom wood (<em>ritmim</em>)" — the sentence on the deceitful tongue uses military and thermal imagery. The arrow (<em>hez</em>) in the OT is frequently the weapon of divine judgment (Ps 7:13; 38:2; 64:7; Job 6:4; Lam 3:12-13). "Broom wood coals (<em>retem</em>)" — the <em>Retama raetam</em> (white broom plant) of the Negev desert produces the hottest-burning, longest-retaining coals known to the ancient world; they remain hot even when appearing extinguished. Elijah rested under a broom tree during his flight from Jezebel (1 Kgs 19:4-5). The combination of sharp arrows and glowing broom coals gives a punishment that is both precise (arrows striking a specific target) and sustained (coals that hold their heat) — the intensity and duration of the judgment matches the intensity and duration of the damage the lying tongue has caused.</p>',
    "5": '<p>"Woe to me, that I must live as a foreigner in Meshech (<em>mashak</em>) and make my dwelling among the tents of Kedar" — Meshech (Gen 10:2) was a people of northern Anatolia, between the Black Sea and Caspian Sea; Kedar (Gen 25:13) was an Arab nomadic confederacy of the Syrian-Arabian desert. These two groups are geographically as far apart as the psalmist could name — separated by thousands of kilometers. Used together as a merism, they represent the furthest extremities of the hostile pagan world: not literal geography (one cannot simultaneously live in Anatolia and Arabia) but the symbolic statement "I am living as far from Zion as it is possible to be, among people as unlike the covenant community as exist." Isaiah uses Meshech (Isa 66:19) and Kedar (Isa 21:16-17; 42:11) in similar "ends of the earth" contexts. The pilgrim who has not yet reached Jerusalem is, in the psalm\'s geography, still in "Meshech and Kedar" — exile from covenant community and the divine presence.</p>',
    "6": '<p>"My soul has lived too long (<em>rabbat shakenah-lah nafshi</em>) among those who hate peace" — the excessive length of the sojourn is the point: not a brief diplomatic visit to hostile territory but a prolonged, wearing residence. "Hate peace (<em>sone shalom</em>)" — <em>shalom</em> encompasses the full covenant vision: communal wellbeing, right relationships, material sufficiency, and divine-human reconciliation. Those who hate <em>shalom</em> are those whose entire orientation is toward disruption, conflict, and the destruction of covenant community order. The phrase identifies the deepest category of the psalm\'s adversaries: not merely those who are angry or competitive with the psalmist personally, but those whose fundamental disposition is against the ordering principle of creation and covenant.</p>',
    "7": '<p>"I am for peace (<em>ani shalom</em>) — but the moment I open my mouth, they want war" — the compressed syntax carries maximum weight: in Hebrew, <em>ani shalom</em> ("I — peace") identifies the entire person with the concept, not merely a preference. "I am peace" is the full identification of self with covenant shalom. The moment of speech is the moment of maximum vulnerability — the psalmist opens his mouth (to speak truth, to seek covenant resolution, to offer peace) and the response is immediate hostility (<em>laqerab</em>, "for battle"). This closing verse of the opening pilgrim psalm frames the entire collection: the journey to Jerusalem is a journey from a world of chronic hostility toward a place where covenant shalom is embodied and practiced — where the lips that are lying in Meshech become the lips of praise at Zion\'s gates.</p>',
  },
  "121": {
    "1": '<p>Psalm 121 is the most beloved of the Songs of Ascents and the most theologically concentrated. The opening question requires careful parsing: "I lift my eyes toward the hills — but where does my help come from?" The hills are <em>not</em> the source of help. In the pilgrimage context the hills might be: (a) the mountains surrounding Jerusalem that the pilgrim ascends; (b) the high places (<em>bamot</em>) on hilltops where pagan shrines were located — explicitly not the source of help; (c) simply the horizon scanned for aid. The question is rhetorical — it sets aside the hills as the source and supplies the correct answer in v2. The Judean hill roads to Jerusalem were genuinely dangerous (Luke 10:30: the Jerusalem-Jericho road was bandit territory; Jer 3:23: "Surely the hills are a delusion"); the pilgrim\'s question about the source of help is both practically urgent and theologically pointed.</p>',
    "2": '<p>"My help comes from the LORD, the maker of heaven and earth (<em>oseh shamayim va\'aretz</em>)" — the incomparability argument: the one who made the mountains is more reliable than the mountains themselves. "Maker of heaven and earth" is one of YHWH\'s most comprehensive titles (Gen 1:1; 14:19, 22; Ps 115:15; 124:8; 134:3; 146:6; Isa 45:18), used throughout the Songs of Ascents to anchor pilgrimage trust in creation-sovereignty. The formula appears again at Ps 124:8 and 134:3 — it functions as the theological bookend of the entire collection: the God of this small pilgrimage journey is the God of the entire cosmos. The Creator who made the terrain the pilgrim walks can certainly govern the pilgrim through it.</p>',
    "3": '<p>"He will not let your foot slip (<em>al-yitten lamot ragleka</em>); your keeper (<em>shomreka</em>) will not slumber (<em>yanum</em>)" — the danger of pilgrimage is concrete: mountain paths, loose stones, and treacherous terrain where a slipped foot could mean injury, delay, or death. The promise applies to the physical path. "Keeper (<em>shomer</em>)" — the word <em>shamar</em> (to keep, guard, watch, preserve) appears six times in 8 verses (vv. 3, 4, 5, 7, 8), an extraordinary concentration that makes divine <em>keeping</em> the theological core of the psalm. The word is used for guarding the garden (Gen 2:15), keeping the covenant (Deut 7:9; Ps 119:2), and guarding the city (Ps 127:1). "Will not slumber" — the first negation of divine sleep, intensified in v4 through staircase parallelism.</p>',
    "4": '<p>"See — he who guards Israel will neither slumber (<em>yanum</em>) nor sleep (<em>yishan</em>)" — the staircase parallelism (<em>maAlot</em>-pattern) of the collection: "slumber" from v3 is picked up in v4, and the statement is doubled and intensified: not merely "will not slumber" but "will neither slumber <em>nor</em> sleep." The theological claim is polemical. In 1 Kgs 18:27, Elijah mocks Baal on Carmel: "Maybe he is sleeping and must be awakened." Egyptian mythology described periods when the sun god Re slept and the sun temporarily failed. The covenant God who keeps Israel is perpetually, vigilantly awake — a flat theological claim that cannot be softened. Even the lament psalms that cry "Awake, O Lord!" (Ps 44:23) do so as an expression of felt abandonment, not as a literal claim that YHWH sleeps; this psalm provides the theological corrective to that idiom.</p>',
    "5": '<p>"The LORD is your keeper; the LORD is your shade (<em>tzillelka</em>) at your right hand" — the third occurrence of "keeper" shifts from third-person cosmic claim ("he who guards Israel") to second-person direct address: "the LORD is <em>your</em> keeper." The personalization is the theological movement. "Shade (<em>tzel</em>) at your right hand" — in the Near Eastern climate where summer temperatures on pilgrimage routes exceed 40°C, shade is survival, not comfort. The "right hand" is the position of protection and honor (Ps 16:8; 110:1; 1 Kgs 2:19; Matt 26:64); in legal settings it is where the advocate stands (Ps 109:31; Zech 3:1-2). YHWH\'s shade at the right hand is thus simultaneously physical protection from the sun\'s heat and covenantal-legal advocacy at the place of greatest vulnerability.</p>',
    "6": '<p>"The sun will not harm you by day (<em>yomam</em>), nor the moon by night (<em>ve\'yareach ballaylah</em>)" — the two great luminaries of Gen 1:14-18, created to "rule over" the day and night, are placed under the divine governance that protects the pilgrim from their harmful aspects. Sunstroke on exposed Judean hill paths was a genuine mortal danger (2 Kgs 4:18-20: the Shunammite\'s son dies of apparent heatstroke). The "harmful moon" reflects the ANE belief in lunar effects on health and sanity — the English word "lunacy" preserves this; <em>seleniazomai</em> (to be moon-struck, Matthew 4:24; 17:15) refers to epileptic-type conditions attributed to lunar influence. YHWH\'s governance of both luminaries means neither the burning of the day nor the mysterious danger of the night can harm the pilgrim who is under divine protection.</p>',
    "7": '<p>"The LORD will protect you from every kind of evil (<em>mikol-ra</em>); he will guard your very life (<em>yishmor et-nafsheka</em>)" — the comprehensive guarantee: the specific protections of vv. 3-6 expand into the total. "Every kind of evil" is not only physical threat but the full range of harm — moral, spiritual, social, circumstantial. "Guard your very life (<em>nefesh</em>)" — <em>nefesh</em> is the comprehensive inner person: totality of life-force, desire, and identity. The soul guarded is the irreducible self that nothing can touch if YHWH guards it. In John 17:12, Jesus draws on the same vocabulary: "While I was with them, I protected them and kept them safe by that name you gave me... None has been lost." The divine keeping of the <em>nefesh</em> in Psalm 121 is the OT template for the NT\'s confidence in eternal security under the Keeper\'s hand.</p>',
    "8": '<p>"The LORD will watch over your coming and going (<em>tzeteka u\'vo\'eka</em>), now and forever (<em>me\'attah ve\'ad-olam</em>)" — "coming and going" is a merism for all of life\'s activity: every departure and return, every beginning and completion (Deut 28:6: "blessed when you come in and when you go out"; 1 Sam 18:16 uses the formula for military leadership; 1 Kgs 3:7 for Solomon\'s governance). The pilgrim who ascends to Jerusalem and returns home — the entire arc of the pilgrimage — is under divine guardianship from start to finish. "Now and forever" — the temporal scope of the protection: not merely for this journey or this lifetime but spanning from the present moment into the unending future. The psalm that began with the dangerous road ends with an eternal promise: the God who guards the pilgrim\'s foot on the path guards the pilgrim\'s <em>nefesh</em> forever.</p>',
  },
  "122": {
    "1": '<p>Psalm 122 is the arrival psalm — the pilgrim has reached Jerusalem. Attributed to David, it reflects the perspective of a worshipper who has heard the summons and is now standing inside the city. "I was filled with joy (<em>samahti</em>) when they said to me, \'Let us go to the house of the LORD!\'" — the invitation to go was itself the occasion of joy, not merely the arrival. In the honor-shame culture of ancient Israel, inclusion in a pilgrimage group was a form of social recognition: to be invited by "they" (the community) to go together to the temple was to be acknowledged as a member of the covenant community. The pilgrimage grammar is communal ("let us go"), not solitary; the joy is triggered by the communal summons, not by private devotion.</p>',
    "2": '<p>"Our feet are standing (<em>hayu omdot</em>) inside your gates, O Jerusalem" — the perfect tense with present force: "have taken their stand." The shift from "I" in v1 to "our feet" in v2 marks the transition from individual invitation to communal arrival — the whole pilgrimage company has reached the destination together. The gates of Jerusalem (<em>she\'arech</em>) were the legal, commercial, and social thresholds of the covenant city; to stand inside them is to be within the city\'s protection and jurisdiction. For pilgrims who had traveled days through the Judean wilderness, this moment of standing inside Jerusalem\'s gates was the physical culmination of the journey. The Songs of Ascents were designed to be sung at precisely this threshold moment — from the outside looking in (Ps 120) to the inside standing in gratitude (Ps 122).</p>',
    "3": '<p>"Jerusalem — built as a city that is closely joined together (<em>shehubberah-lah yahdav</em>)" — the phrase is dense. <em>Habar</em> (to join, to connect, to be united) in the passive participle: the city built as a unit, joined closely to itself. This describes: (a) the physical compactness of Jerusalem\'s construction — the dense, stone-built city where no space was wasted and every wall connected to the next; (b) the social and spiritual unity of the people gathered there — "joined together" in covenant fellowship; (c) the theological joining of earth and heaven at the point where YHWH dwells. The pilgrims who came scattered from twelve tribal territories found in Jerusalem a city that was constitutively unified — the architectural expression of the covenant community\'s unity under one God.</p>',
    "4": '<p>"To which the tribes make their pilgrimage (<em>shevatim alu</em>) — the tribes of the LORD (<em>shivte-yah</em>) — as it was commanded of Israel, to give thanks to the name of the LORD" — the three great pilgrimage festivals (Exod 23:14-17; Deut 16:16) required every male Israelite to "appear before the LORD" at the central sanctuary. <em>Shivte-yah</em> (tribes of the LORD) — the possessive suffix on the divine name is unusual and emphatic: these are not merely Israelite tribes but YHWH\'s own tribes, his covenant possession. The pilgrimage is both obligation ("as it was commanded") and identity expression: the tribes go up because this is who they are — YHWH\'s people returning to their God\'s house. The Feast of Tabernacles had an eschatological dimension; Zech 14:16-19 envisions all nations eventually ascending to Jerusalem for Sukkot.</p>',
    "5": '<p>"There the thrones of judgment stand (<em>kisseot lemishpat</em>) — the thrones belonging to the house of David" — the administrative-judicial center of Israel was at Jerusalem. Covenant law required difficult legal cases to be brought to the central sanctuary for adjudication (Deut 17:8-13: "go to the Levitical priests and to the judge who is in office at that time; they will give you the verdict"). The "thrones of the house of David" represent the royal judicial function — the king\'s responsibility to administer justice, particularly for the poor and powerless (Ps 72:1-4; Isa 9:7; 11:4; Jer 22:3, 15-16). The pilgrimage to Jerusalem was simultaneously access to the highest human court of appeal in Israel: justice and worship were not separate categories at Zion. The pilgrim went up to pray <em>and</em> to access covenant law.</p>',
    "6": '<p>"Pray for the peace of Jerusalem (<em>shaalu shlom yerushalayim</em>)! May all who love this city flourish (<em>yishlayyu ohavayik</em>)" — the wordplay between <em>Yerushalayim</em> (Jerusalem) and <em>shalom</em> (peace) is almost certainly intentional; the city\'s name contains the very thing being prayed for. The popular etymology (debated academically) connects Jerusalem to <em>shalem</em> (wholeness, completeness) from which <em>shalom</em> derives. To pray for Jerusalem\'s peace is to pray for what is written into the city\'s name — for her to become what she is called to be. <em>Shaál</em> (to ask, inquire, petition) suggests formal prayer, not merely a wish; the pilgrimage community is being instructed in an intercession practice that continued throughout Israel\'s history and into the synagogue\'s daily prayers (the <em>Amidah</em>\'s 14th benediction prays for Jerusalem\'s restoration).</p>',
    "7": '<p>"May there be peace within your walls (<em>bechélech shalom</em>) and safety (<em>shalvah</em>) within your strongholds (<em>be\'armenotayik</em>)" — the two layers of the city\'s defensive architecture: the outer wall rampart (<em>hel</em>) and the inner palatial fortresses (<em>armon</em>). Peace within walls and security within strongholds represents both the political stability of the city and the social ordering of its internal life. The pilgrim who just arrived (v2) now prays for the city\'s sustained wellbeing — not merely as a visitor benefiting from its peace but as a covenant community member whose flourishing is bound up with Jerusalem\'s flourishing. Jeremiah 29:7 ("seek the peace of the city where I have sent you into exile") extended this prayer practice even to Babylon: the covenant community prays for the peace of whatever city it inhabits.</p>',
    "8": '<p>"For the sake of my brothers and friends (<em>ahai ve\'re\'ai</em>) I say, \'May peace be with you!\'" — the pilgrimage city is where the covenant network of brothers and friends is located. In the ancient world, "brothers" and "friends" were not merely biological or personal categories but represented the covenant kinship network — those with whom one had binding obligations of loyalty and mutual aid. The three great festivals gathered the dispersed community in one place, maintaining the social bonds that geographic distance would otherwise dissolve. To pray for Jerusalem\'s peace for the sake of brothers and friends is to pray for the social fabric that makes covenant community possible: the network of mutual obligation, shared worship, and reciprocal loyalty that the pilgrimage system was designed to sustain.</p>',
    "9": '<p>"For the sake of the house of the LORD our God (<em>beit-YHWH eloheinu</em>) I will work for your wellbeing (<em>avakshah tov lak</em>)" — the ultimate motivation for Jerusalem\'s wellbeing is theological, not merely social. The house of YHWH (<em>beit-YHWH</em>) is the temple, the covenant dwelling-point where heaven and earth intersect. To seek Jerusalem\'s good "for the sake of the house of the LORD" is to recognize that the city\'s welfare is inseparable from the welfare of worship. The practical commitment (<em>avakesh</em>, "I will seek, actively pursue, work toward") goes beyond prayer into action — the pilgrim becomes an agent of the city\'s wellbeing upon returning home, because the house of YHWH that stands in it is the source of all blessing that flows outward to the covenant community and from there to the nations (Pss 67:1-2; 96:3).</p>',
  },
  "123": {
    "1": '<p>Psalm 123 is a communal psalm of petition during a period of social contempt and foreign oppression. The opening posture — eyes lifted to the enthroned God — is the prayer-posture of the expectant servant: "To you I lift my eyes (<em>elecha nasati et-einai</em>), O you who sit enthroned (<em>hayoshevi</em>) in the heavens!" The divine enthronement in heaven is the spatial claim that grounds all petition: YHWH is at the highest possible point, from which he sees all and from which no human power can dislodge him. To lift eyes to the enthroned one is to direct attention away from the circumstances of contempt (vv. 3-4) and toward the one who governs from above those circumstances. Ps 11:4; 113:5-6 use the same enthroned-heavens imagery of the God who "looks down" on human affairs from his elevated position.</p>',
    "2": '<p>"As the eyes of a servant watch the hand of his master, as a maidservant\'s eyes follow the hand of her mistress, so our eyes watch the LORD our God" — the ANE household communication protocol that supplies the psalm\'s central image. In a high-status household, verbal commands were often replaced by silent hand-signals: a gesture of the master\'s hand directed the servant to the next task, summoned them, or dismissed them. The servant who watched the hand most carefully was the most responsive and the most trusted — the one promoted to greater responsibility. The prayer-posture of watching the divine hand is thus not passive subjection but attentive readiness: the covenant community watches for the divine signal, prepared to respond immediately to whatever YHWH indicates. Both male (<em>eved</em>) and female (<em>shifhah</em>) servants are named, making the image comprehensive: all of the covenant community — not just one gender or class — holds this position of attentive watchfulness before YHWH.</p>',
    "3": '<p>"Have mercy on us, O LORD, have mercy on us (<em>honenu YHWH honenu</em>) — for we have endured far more than our fill of contempt (<em>buz</em>)" — the doubled imperative conveys both urgency and exhaustion: the community has waited so long that the standard petition must be intensified. <em>Buz</em> (contempt, scorn, the disregard of the powerful for the powerless) is one of the most painful social wounds in the honor-shame world — to be held in contempt was to be publicly designated as without honor, beneath notice, unworthy of serious engagement. This is not anger (which at least acknowledges the other person\'s significance) but dismissal: the contemptuous person does not bother to hate — they simply disregard. The community has been "glutted" with contempt (<em>rabbat savenah-lah nafshenu</em>, "our soul is fully sated — overfull") — they have consumed what should never have been on their plate at all.</p>',
    "4": '<p>"We have had more than our fill of the mockery of the comfortable (<em>shaalvei</em>) and the contempt of the arrogant (<em>ge\'im</em>)" — the social profile of those whose contempt the community endures: <em>shaalvei</em> (those at ease, prosperous, undisturbed, comfortable) and <em>ge\'im</em> (the arrogant, the haughty). The comfortable have been insulated from suffering by their prosperity; their contempt flows from having never been desperate or powerless. The arrogant have elevated themselves above their proper station and regard the covenant community from that false elevation. The psalm\'s petition to the enthroned God (v1) is motivated by this social structure: those who despise the community occupy positions of earthly height; the only height from which they can be overturned is the height of divine enthronement — where YHWH sits above them all.</p>',
  },
  "124": {
    "1": '<p>Psalm 124, attributed to David, is a communal thanksgiving for deliverance from a threat that is described vividly but without historical specification — the deliberate anonymity makes the psalm reusable across the community\'s generations. "If the LORD had not been on our side (<em>lule YHWH shehayah lanu</em>) — let Israel say it now (<em>yomar-na Yisra\'el</em>)" — the liturgical prompt invites the congregation to corporate recital. "Let Israel say it now" is a call-and-response structure; the community participates in the confession that YHWH\'s presence made the difference. The conditional particle <em>lule</em> (if not, had it not been for) opens an imagined counter-history of what would have happened without divine intervention — and the imagination of the disaster that did not happen makes the thanksgiving for the deliverance that did happen more intense.</p>',
    "2": '<p>"If the LORD had not been on our side when our enemies rose up against us" — the repetition of v1\'s opening line intensifies through liturgical reduplication. "Our enemies rose up (<em>qum aleinu adam</em>)" — <em>qum</em> (to rise up) with the preposition "against" is the military or legal posture of the adversary rising to attack, accuse, or overwhelm. <em>Adam</em> (humanity, human beings) — not supernatural enemies but human adversaries. The acknowledgment that human power without divine counter-action would have sufficed to destroy the community is the covenant confession of human weakness: Israel\'s survival is not self-explanatory from a human-power analysis but requires the theological category of divine presence on Israel\'s side.</p>',
    "3": '<p>"They would have swallowed us whole (<em>hayyim bila\'unu</em>) when their fury blazed against us" — <em>bala</em> (to swallow, to engulf, to consume entirely) is used of the earth swallowing Korah, Dathan, and Abiram alive (Num 16:30-33), of Sheol swallowing the living (Prov 1:12; Isa 5:14), and of the great fish swallowing Jonah (Jon 1:17). The chaos-monster imagery runs through all these uses: the threat is not merely defeat but total consumption, dissolution into the chaos-realm. "Swallowed <em>alive</em> (<em>hayyim</em>)" — the horror is the vitality of the victim at the moment of engulfing: not the dead body disposed of but living persons consumed. The "fury (<em>haron</em>) blazing" — the incendiary anger as the heat that drives the swallowing — creates an overwhelming image of existential threat that would have been total without YHWH\'s intervention.</p>',
    "4": '<p>"The rushing waters (<em>mayim</em>) would have swept us away; the current (<em>nahalah</em>) would have poured over us" — the imagery shifts from the consuming mouth (v3) to the consuming flood. The water imagery (vv. 4-5) draws on the primordial chaos-water tradition: the flood that overwhelms ordered creation (Gen 6-8), the threatening sea that YHWH subdues at creation (Gen 1:2; Ps 93:3-4), the waters of the lament tradition (Ps 69:1-2; 144:7). A <em>nahal</em> (wadi, seasonal stream) in the Negev can go from bone-dry to catastrophic flash-flood within minutes when distant rains fall — the "current that poured over us" was viscerally familiar to anyone in Palestine: sudden, overwhelming torrents with no warning were one of the landscape\'s genuine mortal hazards. The natural world\'s danger maps onto the social danger of overwhelming enemies.</p>',
    "5": '<p>"The raging waves (<em>hamayim hazedonim</em>) would have overwhelmed us completely" — <em>zedonim</em> are literally "the insolent, presumptuous, proud waters" — waters that have exceeded their appointed boundaries. In OT creation theology, the waters are given their place and commanded not to cross it (Job 38:8-11; Ps 104:7-9; Prov 8:29; Jer 5:22). "Insolent waters" that have overflowed their limits are waters that have rejected the divine ordering of creation — they represent not merely a natural disaster but a cosmic rebellion against order. The enemies who threaten the community are like these presumptuous waters: they have exceeded the bounds of the divinely permitted, and the divine response is to restrain them as YHWH restrains the sea.</p>',
    "6": '<p>"Praise be to the LORD — he did not hand us over as prey (<em>teref</em>) to their teeth!" — the predatory-animal image follows the swallowing, flood, and bird-snare images of the psalm: YHWH has prevented the community from becoming <em>teref</em> (torn meat, prey ripped by a predator\'s teeth). The blessing of YHWH is articulated as negation: "He did <em>not</em>..." — the deliverance is defined by the catastrophe that did not occur. This structure of praise-through-negation (praising what YHWH prevented rather than what YHWH accomplished) is a distinctive feature of the deliverance thanksgiving: the most intense gratitude often arises from contemplating the disaster averted. <em>Baruk YHWH</em> (praised/blessed be the LORD) — the blessing formula that acknowledges YHWH as the source of all good and the averted disaster as his gift.</p>',
    "7": '<p>"We have gotten away like a bird that slips out of the hunter\'s trap (<em>pah yoqshim</em>) — the snare is broken (<em>hannipah</em>), and we are free!" — the bird-and-snare image is one of the Psalter\'s most vivid escape metaphors (also Pss 91:3; 141:9; Prov 6:5; 7:23). The trap-setter (<em>yaqush</em>) is the professional fowler who spreads his net or springs his snare — a skill requiring patience, concealment, and knowledge of the bird\'s habits. The <em>pah</em> (snare, spring-trap) snapped shut on the bird\'s foot. When the snare breaks, the bird escapes not by strength but by the mechanical failure of the trapping device: freedom comes not from the bird\'s power but from the failure of what held it. YHWH\'s intervention is precisely this snare-breaking: the trap set by the enemy is neutralized from outside, and the community escapes because the device that held them has been broken by the divine hand.</p>',
    "8": '<p>"Our help comes from the name of the LORD (<em>beshem YHWH</em>), the maker of heaven and earth" — the closing verse echoes Ps 121:2 nearly exactly ("my help comes from the LORD, the maker of heaven and earth"), functioning as a liturgical refrain that bookends the collection\'s opening. The addition "in the name of" emphasizes the <em>shem</em> (name) of YHWH — which encompasses his character, his acts, and his entire history of faithfulness. To say "our help is in the name of YHWH" is to invoke that entire covenant history as the ground of present confidence. "Maker of heaven and earth" closes the psalm with the same cosmic scope with which it opened: the God who delivered from human enemies is the God who made everything those enemies stood on.</p>',
  },
  "125": {
    "1": '<p>Psalm 125 is a psalm of trust using the physical geography of Jerusalem as its controlling metaphor. "Those who trust in the LORD (<em>habotehim baYHWH</em>) are as firm as Mount Zion — unmovable, enduring forever" — the theology of trust is expressed through the geology of the city. Mount Zion had become, for Israelite theology, the symbol of divine stability — not because of the mountain\'s size (it is modest by world standards) but because of what YHWH had chosen to do there. The covenant promise of Ps 132:14 ("this is my resting place forever") made Zion theologically immovable regardless of its physical vulnerability. To trust in YHWH is to have the stability of the mountain that YHWH has claimed: unshakeable not because of inherent strength but because of the divine commitment that underwrites it.</p>',
    "2": '<p>"Just as the mountains encircle Jerusalem (<em>harim saviv li\'rushalayim</em>), so the LORD encircles his people, now and forever" — the physical topography of Jerusalem provides the metaphor: the city sits in a basin surrounded by the Mount of Olives to the east, Mount Scopus to the northeast, and higher ground on the west and south. A traveler arriving at Jerusalem found the city visually enclosed by hills on all sides — a natural geographic encirclement that the psalm transforms into a theological image. As the hills surround the city providing natural shelter, YHWH surrounds his people with divine protection that is permanent ("now and forever"). The landscape the pilgrim walks through becomes a living parable of divine guardianship: even the topography preaches the gospel of YHWH\'s encircling care.</p>',
    "3": '<p>"The scepter of the wicked will not be allowed to remain (<em>lo yanuah</em>) over the territory given to the righteous, lest the righteous be tempted to do wrong" — the political-moral concern: foreign domination (the "scepter of the wicked") over covenant land creates an ongoing moral hazard for the righteous. If wicked rulers govern long enough, the righteous will be tempted to accommodate, collaborate, or imitate their methods — to survive by becoming like the oppressor. The psalm names this moral danger explicitly: the <em>duration</em> of wicked rule matters, not just its fact. YHWH\'s covenant promise includes the guarantee that wicked rule over the righteous\'s territory will not be permanent — a promise that sustained Jewish hope through Babylonian, Persian, Seleucid, and Roman domination and continues to frame the theology of political oppression.</p>',
    "4": '<p>"Bless those who are good (<em>tovim</em>), O LORD, and all who are upright in heart (<em>yesharim belibbotam</em>)" — the petition for blessing upon the covenant faithful is the positive counterpart to the implied judgment on the wicked. The pairing of "good" (<em>tov</em>) and "upright" (<em>yashar</em>) identifies both external behavior and internal orientation: the good person does good; the upright person has an inner alignment with divine standards. "In heart (<em>belibbotam</em>)" — the heart as the seat of intention and moral orientation (Jer 17:9-10; Ps 51:10; 1 Sam 16:7: "the LORD looks at the heart"). The blessing petition assumes that YHWH distinguishes between those whose uprightness is external performance and those whose hearts are genuinely aligned with the covenant values — and blesses the latter.</p>',
    "5": '<p>"But as for those who swerve onto crooked paths (<em>hamattim aqalqallotam</em>), the LORD will banish them along with those who do evil. Peace be upon Israel (<em>shalom al-Yisra\'el</em>)" — those who "swerve" (<em>natah</em>, to turn aside, to deviate) onto "crooked paths" (<em>aqalqallot</em>, twisted, winding, devious routes) are those who deviate from the straight covenant path while maintaining the outward appearance of covenant community membership. The wisdom tradition consistently contrasts the straight path (<em>derek yashar</em>) with the crooked path of the wicked (Prov 2:15; 4:26-27; 11:20; 28:6, 10). "Peace be upon Israel" is the closing liturgical blessing — the same formula ends Ps 128:6 and is applied to the church in Gal 6:16. The Songs of Ascents consistently close with this covenant-community blessing, connecting the individual pilgrim\'s journey to the communal <em>shalom</em> that is the goal of all pilgrimage.</p>',
  },
  "126": {
    "1": '<p>Psalm 126 explicitly references the return from Babylonian exile, though interpreters debate whether it describes the return as past (vv. 1-3) and prays for its completion (vv. 4-6), or whether vv. 1-3 recall an earlier restoration and vv. 4-6 pray for a further return. "When the LORD restored the fortunes of Zion (<em>shuv YHWH et-shivut Tziyyon</em>)" — the phrase <em>shuv shevut</em> (to restore fortunes/captivity) is a technical term for the reversal of exile conditions (Deut 30:3; Jer 29:14; 30:3, 18; Ezek 16:53; 39:25; Amos 9:14). "We were like people in a dream (<em>keholomim</em>)" — the return from Babylon was so improbable, so contrary to all historical expectation (the Mesopotamian empires did not release conquered peoples), that the community experienced it as a dream from which they feared waking. Cyrus\'s edict of 538 BCE (Ezra 1:1-4) must have had exactly this quality of unreality for those who had accepted exile as a multigenerational permanent reality.</p>',
    "2": '<p>"Then our mouths were full of laughter (<em>sehok</em>) and our tongues rang out with shouts of joy (<em>rinnah</em>); the nations were saying, \'The LORD has done great things for them!\'" — laughter and the ringing joyful cry are the involuntary, uncontrollable responses to overwhelming joy — the body\'s speech when ordinary words are insufficient. The nations\' testimony is remarkable: the community did not need to claim the miracle — the surrounding nations named it independently. "The LORD has done great things for them" is what the outsiders saw and said; v3 repeats it as the community\'s own confession. YHWH\'s faithfulness to his covenant people becomes visible to the nations as a world-historical testimony to divine character — the same mechanism as the Exodus, where Rahab (Josh 2:10-11) and Jethro (Exod 18:9-11) testified to YHWH\'s power through what they had witnessed.</p>',
    "3": '<p>"The LORD has done great things for us — and we are overjoyed (<em>hayinu semehim</em>)" — the community\'s echo of the nations\' witness: the covenant people claim in their own voice what the nations observed from outside. The joy is stated as an achieved state (<em>hayah</em>): "we have come to be overjoyed" — not a momentary feeling but a settled condition resulting from the recognition of what YHWH has done. The pilgrimage community singing this psalm on the ascent to Jerusalem re-lived the restoration moment liturgically: each pilgrimage recapitulated the return from exile, the journey from scattered foreignness (Ps 120) to covenant community joy at Zion (Ps 134).</p>',
    "4": '<p>"Restore our fortunes, O LORD (<em>shuvah YHWH et-shevitenu</em>), like the streams that suddenly fill the desert wadis (<em>ka\'afiqim banegev</em>)" — the petition uses the distinctive climate of the Negev as its image. The wadis (seasonal riverbeds, <em>afiqim</em>) of the Negev desert are bone-dry channels during the summer months — then, when the winter rains fall, they fill suddenly and catastrophically with rushing water, transforming from dusty gullies into torrents within hours. The restoration of the exiled community is compared to this sudden, dramatic, landscape-changing inrush of water: not a gradual trickle but a flash-flood abundance that fills what was completely empty in one event. The petition asks for the rest of the return to happen with this quality of sudden completeness rather than the slow, partial dribble of historical return.</p>',
    "5": '<p>"Those who plant in tears (<em>bedim\'ah</em>) will harvest with shouts of joy (<em>berinnah</em>)" — the agricultural wisdom tradition transformed into eschatological promise. In the ancient Near East, the sowing season coincided with the period of maximum agricultural anxiety: the farmer planted seed during uncertain drought conditions, weeping from the anxiety of not knowing if rain would come, or from the sacrifice of using scarce food-grain as seed. The harvest came in joy when the seed that was planted in weeping produced its fruit. The pattern maps directly onto the exile-then-return narrative: the years of Babylonian captivity were the weeping sowing season; the return and restoration are the harvest-joy. Paul extends this pattern: "whoever sows sparingly will also reap sparingly, and whoever sows generously will also reap generously" (2 Cor 9:6); John 16:20-22 applies it to the disciples\' grief at the crucifixion becoming joy at the resurrection.</p>',
    "6": '<p>"The one who sets out weeping (<em>halok yelech uvacho</em>), carrying the seed bag (<em>nose meshe-hazaral</em>), will come home with joyful shouts (<em>yavo berinnah</em>), loaded down with the harvest (<em>nose alumotav</em>)" — the agricultural image is rendered in its full sequential detail: departure (weeping, carrying seed), return (shouting, loaded with sheaves). The transformation is total: the same person who left weeping returns rejoicing; the same hands that carried the seed bag now carry the harvest bundle. This is not mere consolation (joy will come eventually) but structural promise: the weeping of sowing and the joy of harvest are phases of the same process, inseparable. For the exile community, this meant that the tears of Babylon were not wasted or lost but were precisely the sowing season of which the return was the harvest — a theology of suffering-as-seed that the NT will develop into the theology of the cross as the sowing of the grain of wheat (John 12:24).</p>',
  },
  "127": {
    "1": '<p>Psalm 127, attributed to Solomon in its superscription, is the only wisdom psalm in the Songs of Ascents collection. Its placement is remarkable: the psalm about YHWH as the true builder of house and city is placed in the mouth of Solomon — the man who built both the temple and the royal palace. "Unless the LORD builds the house (<em>yivneh bayit</em>), the builders work to no purpose (<em>shav amelu bonav bo</em>)" — the house (<em>bayit</em>) encompasses both the physical dwelling and the household/family unit (the OT uses <em>bayit</em> for both). The claim is not that human building is irrelevant but that human building without divine initiative and support is ultimately purposeless. Solomon\'s temple was the greatest construction achievement of ancient Israel — and this psalm insists that it was YHWH who built it, not Solomon.</p>',
    "2": '<p>"It is pointless to rise before dawn and work until dark (<em>meshane lahem</em>), eating meals of anxious toil (<em>lehem ha\'atzavim</em>) — for the LORD gives sleep as a gift to his beloved (<em>shenah lididov</em>)" — the <em>lehem ha\'atzavim</em> (bread of anxious labor/pain) is the food produced by overwork driven by anxiety rather than trust — an echo of the Eden curse (Gen 3:17-19: "by painful toil you will eat of it all the days of your life"). YHWH gives sleep as a gift to his <em>yedid</em> (beloved, the one he loves — the same word as Jedidiah, the covenant name given to Solomon in 2 Sam 12:25). The gift of sleep signifies that the covenant person does not need to anxiously overwork because YHWH is working while they sleep. This is the theology of Sabbath applied to daily life: the day of rest is possible because YHWH governs and provides even when human effort has stopped.</p>',
    "3": '<p>"Yes, children are a gift from the LORD (<em>nahalat YHWH</em>); they are a reward he gives (<em>sakar</em>)" — <em>nahalah</em> (inheritance, allotment, what is assigned by God) is the term for the tribal land grants in Joshua: children are a gift-allotment from YHWH in the same way the promised land was a gift-allotment. The transfer of meaning from territorial inheritance to children is significant: what YHWH gives as covenant gift in the land-dimension, he also gives in the family-dimension. <em>Sakar</em> (reward, wages, payment) complements <em>nahalah</em>: children are what is received as the fruit of one\'s covenantal life, as wages are received for work done. The combination of inheritance (unconditional gift) and reward (responsive to faithfulness) captures the dual character of covenant blessing.</p>',
    "4": '<p>"Children born in a man\'s prime (<em>bene hane\'urim</em>) are like arrows in the hand of a soldier" — children born in a man\'s youth grow to adulthood while he is still vigorous, giving him strong adult sons at his side during his later years. The arrow image: arrows are weapons that extend a warrior\'s reach beyond his immediate physical range — they act at a distance. Adult sons extended the father\'s legal, economic, and social reach beyond his own person: they could testify on his behalf, conduct business, represent the household in multiple locations simultaneously. "In the hand of a soldier" — arrows in the hand are ready for immediate use; adult sons at the father\'s side are similarly available and capable.</p>',
    "5": '<p>"How blessed is the man who has his quiver full of them! He will not be put to shame when he faces his enemies at the city gate (<em>basha\'ar</em>)" — the city gate was the social, legal, and commercial center of ancient Israelite life: contracts were ratified there (Ruth 4:1-12), legal disputes were adjudicated there (Deut 21:19; 22:15; 25:7; Job 29:7; 31:21; Prov 31:23), and political decisions were announced there (2 Sam 15:2; 2 Kgs 7:1). To have "enemies at the gate" who challenge your legal standing, your debts, or your honor required witnesses and advocates. A man with many adult sons had multiple witnesses who could testify on his behalf and advocates who could press his legal case. The quiver full of arrows/sons meant legal security in the gate-court — the place where one\'s standing in the covenant community was publicly negotiated.</p>',
  },
  "128": {
    "1": '<p>Psalm 128 is a covenant beatitude psalm — <em>ashre</em> (how blessed/happy) opening the description of the ideal covenant household. "How blessed is every person (<em>kol-ish</em>) who fears the LORD (<em>yere YHWH</em>) and walks in his ways" — the blessing is inclusive: "every person" is the scope, not merely the particularly devout or the king. "Fear of the LORD" is the foundational wisdom disposition: not terror but reverential awe, the orientation of the whole person toward YHWH as the source of all wisdom and the ground of all right living (Prov 1:7; 9:10; Ps 111:10). "Walks in his ways (<em>holech bidrakhav</em>)" — the walking metaphor for covenant obedience: not a static position but a continuous, directional movement through life in conformity with the covenant pattern.</p>',
    "2": '<p>"You will enjoy the fruit of your labor (<em>yegiah kapecha</em>); you will be blessed, and things will go well for you" — the covenant blessing of productive labor: the fruit of one\'s work will be enjoyed by the worker. This is the reversal of several biblical curses: the Eden curse (Gen 3:17-19: others will eat what you labor for) and the covenant curse of Deut 28:30-33 (you will plant vineyards but not drink the wine; others will eat your crops). The blessed household is one where the connection between labor and its fruit is intact: the worker receives what the work produces. <em>Yegiah kapecha</em> ("the labor of your hands/palms") — the word <em>yegiah</em> can carry the weight of toil, effort, and even hardship; the blessing is not that the labor is effortless but that its fruit is received.</p>',
    "3": '<p>"Your wife will be like a fruitful vine (<em>gefen poriyyah</em>) flourishing within your home; your children like young olive shoots (<em>shitele zeitim</em>) gathered around your table" — two agricultural images for the blessed household. The vine (<em>gefen</em>) as image of the productive wife: vines require careful tending, are vulnerable in early years, and become remarkably productive over time; they produce not just food but the wine of celebration. The olive shoots (<em>shitele zeitim</em>) as image of children: young olive trees gathered in a cluster around the central trunk, the household table as the gathering point. Both images are agricultural realities that the Judean household would recognize: the vineyard and the olive grove were the primary sources of covenant-land prosperity.</p>',
    "4": '<p>"This is the blessing that comes to the man who fears the LORD (<em>yere YHWH</em>)" — the verse functions as a summary conclusion for vv. 2-3 before expanding the horizon in vv. 5-6. The repetition of "fears the LORD" brackets the household-blessing section (vv. 1 and 4) and confirms that the material blessing of the household is the covenant blessing — not a general prosperity gospel but the specific covenant promise attached to the specific covenant orientation of fear-of-YHWH. The Deuteronomic covenant structure (Deut 28:1-14) specifies exactly this: obedience to YHWH\'s ways produces material blessing in children, crops, and flocks. Psalm 128 is the liturgical celebration of this covenant dynamic.</p>',
    "5": '<p>"May the LORD bless you from Zion (<em>yevarechecha YHWH miTziyyon</em>); may you see Jerusalem flourish all the days of your life" — the blessing extends from the household to the city. The source of blessing is Zion — the temple-mountain where YHWH\'s presence dwells — and the blessing flows outward from there to the individual household. The pilgrim who has come from the individual household to Zion is given the blessing of Zion to take back to the household: the movement is bidirectional. "See Jerusalem flourish (<em>urine betov Yerushalayim</em>)" — the pilgrimage city\'s wellbeing is the frame within which the individual household flourishes; personal blessing and covenant community blessing are not separable in the Psalter\'s theology.</p>',
    "6": '<p>"May you live to see your grandchildren (<em>benei vanecha</em>). Peace be upon Israel (<em>shalom al-Yisra\'el</em>)" — the temporal extension of the blessing: long enough to see the third generation, grandchildren, is the sign of maximal covenant blessing in the OT (Gen 50:23: Joseph saw Ephraim\'s children to the third generation; Job 42:16: Job saw four generations). The blessing extends from individual (v1-2) to household (v3-4) to city (v5) to nation (v6). "Peace be upon Israel" closes with the same covenant-community blessing that closes Ps 125:5 — the individual pilgrimage blessing is always ultimately corporate: the personal flourishing of the covenant household contributes to and participates in the <em>shalom</em> of the whole covenant people.</p>',
  },
  "129": {
    "1": '<p>Psalm 129 is a communal lament over historical persecutions, using an agricultural metaphor for oppression. The opening call to recital echoes Ps 124:1: "Again and again they have attacked me since my earliest days (<em>me\'ne\'urai</em>) — let Israel say this now" — the liturgical invitation to corporate recitation of historical suffering. "Since my earliest days" (since my youth) — the corporate "Israel" speaks as an individual: the personification of the nation as a person who has suffered from youth, from the very beginning of its existence as a people. Egypt, Canaan, Assyria, Babylon — Israel\'s enemies since youth. The pilgrim community saying this psalm on the ascent to Jerusalem was re-living the entire history of national persecution as a shared identity narrative.</p>',
    "2": '<p>"Again and again they have attacked me since my earliest days, and yet they have never overcome me (<em>lo yakhlu li</em>)" — the repetition of v1a in v2a is both staircase parallelism and liturgical emphasis: the congregation says it twice, and the second time the conclusion is added: "and yet they have never overcome me." The confession of suffering and the confession of survival are inseparable: Israel\'s whole history of persecution is also the history of never-conquered survival. The "never overcome" is the theological claim at the center of the psalm: multiple empires have attacked, but none has managed to destroy the covenant community. This is not triumphalism (the suffering is real) but covenant confidence (the suffering does not have the last word).</p>',
    "3": '<p>"They plowed across my back like farmers cutting their furrows (<em>harashim harashim al-gavi</em>); they made them long and deep (<em>he\'eriku lema\'anitam</em>)" — the plowing metaphor for oppression is one of the Psalter\'s most arresting images. The agricultural image is precise: plowing opens the earth by cutting long, deep furrows; the oxen pull the plow across the field with sustained, repeated force. To plow across a person\'s back with the same force and sustained repetition is to describe sustained, methodical torture or oppression — not a single blow but a systematic, agricultural-scale assault on the body/community. The "long furrows" suggest the extended duration of the oppression: not a brief attack but a sustained agricultural operation of destruction.</p>',
    "4": '<p>"But the LORD is righteous (<em>YHWH tzaddik</em>) — he has cut through the ropes (<em>qitzetz abot</em>) the wicked used to bind me" — the ropes (<em>avot</em>, braided cords, harness ropes) that attach the plow to the oxen: YHWH has cut through the ropes that connected the plowing instrument to the power behind it, severing the mechanism of oppression. Isa 10:27 uses the same image of the Assyrian yoke being broken: "the yoke will be broken because of the anointing." <em>Tzaddik</em> (righteous, just) — YHWH\'s righteousness is what motivates the cutting of the ropes: because YHWH upholds the right order, oppression cannot continue indefinitely. The divine righteousness is not an abstract attribute but an active force that cuts through the structures of oppression.</p>',
    "5": '<p>"May every one who hates Zion (<em>sone Tziyyon</em>) be put to shame and driven back" — the imprecatory petition for the reversal of Zion\'s enemies. "Hates Zion" — in the biblical framework, Zion is not merely a city but the covenant dwelling of YHWH; to hate Zion is to hate what YHWH has chosen and where YHWH dwells. The petition for shame (<em>boshet</em>) and retreat (<em>nasog ahor</em>) is a request for the same reversal-of-fortune that the psalm has described in Israel\'s history: those who attacked Israel from her youth have been driven back repeatedly; may this continue. The imprecation is not vengeance (personal retaliation) but justice-petition: may the enemies of the covenant community receive the consequences of opposing the divine choice.</p>',
    "6": '<p>"May they be like grass growing on a flat rooftop (<em>hasot gag</em>), which withers before it even has a chance to grow" — the rooftop grass image: flat roofs in ancient Israel were typically beaten earth or plaster, and any vegetation that sprouted in the cracks had no significant depth of soil. Whatever grass grew on a rooftop was rootless, thin, and unable to survive the drying sun without any water retention. It grew quickly (easily visible green shoots in the first spring rain) and withered almost immediately when the rains stopped — "before it has a chance to grow" is literally "before it has been plucked up" (implying it never reaches harvestable height). The image is of impressive initial appearance that amounts to nothing at all.</p>',
    "7": '<p>"No reaper ever fills his hands with it, and no one gathers it into sheaves" — the agricultural futility image completed: the rooftop grass cannot be harvested because it produces nothing harvestable. The reaper who fills his hands with grain from a good field (Ruth 2:3: Boaz\'s reapers filling their hands with cut grain) finds nothing to fill his hands on the rooftop. The sheave-binder who follows behind the reaper has nothing to bundle. The wicked\'s prosperity, like rooftop grass, looks alive but produces no harvest — no lasting fruit, no accumulated legacy, no genuine yield from the brief display of apparent vitality.</p>',
    "8": '<p>"And no one passing by will say, \'The LORD\'s blessing be on you! We pronounce blessing over you in the name of the LORD.\'" — the harvest blessing was a formal social exchange between the landowner and the reapers in his field (Ruth 2:4: "Boaz greeted the harvesters and said, \'The LORD be with you!\' and they responded, \'The LORD bless you!\'"  — this is the exchange described in Ps 129:8). The blessing between landowner and reaper was the covenant social seal on a successful harvest. The wicked who produce rooftop-grass prosperity receive no such exchange: no one blesses them in the name of YHWH because there is no harvest to bless, no fruit to celebrate, no covenant community that shares in what they have produced.</p>',
  },
  "130": {
    "1": '<p>Psalm 130, known since the Latin Vulgate as the <em>De Profundis</em> ("Out of the depths"), is one of the seven traditional penitential psalms (Pss 6, 32, 38, 51, 102, 130, 143), used in Christian liturgy since the early church for Ash Wednesday and the Office of the Dead. It is also the foundation of Luther\'s most famous chorale, "Aus tiefer Not schrei ich zu dir" (1524), which became a defining text of Reformation theology of grace. "From the depths of despair (<em>mima\'amakim</em>) I cry out to you, O LORD" — the <em>mamakim</em> (depths, deeps) are the place of maximum distance from God and from light: the depths of the sea that cover the drowned (Exod 15:5; Neh 9:11), the depths of Sheol (Ps 86:13; Isa 7:11; Ezek 26:20), the depths of distress and alienation. The De Profundis prayer begins at the lowest possible point and goes up.</p>',
    "2": '<p>"O Lord, hear my voice; let your ears be open to my pleading (<em>tihenah oznecha qashuvot leqol tahnunai</em>)" — the double petition for auditory attention: "hear my voice" (basic reception) and "let your ears be open to my pleading" (attentive, responsive engagement). <em>Tahanun</em> (pleading, supplication, the prayer that seeks grace) — the root <em>hanan</em> (to be gracious, to show favor) is embedded in the word: the supplication is itself a plea for grace. The address shifts from the tetragrammaton (<em>YHWH</em>) in v1 to <em>Adonai</em> (Lord, my master) — a shift in register from the covenant name to the relational title, emphasizing the petition\'s personal, dependent character. The ears being "open" (<em>qashuvot</em>, attentive, alert) is the anthropomorphic image of God leaning in to hear, the posture of engaged listening.</p>',
    "3": '<p>"If you, O LORD, kept a record of sins (<em>tishmor-avonot</em>), Lord, who could stand before you (<em>mi ya\'amod</em>)?" — the foundational argument for divine forgiveness: if YHWH maintained the full, accurate covenant ledger of infractions, no human being could survive divine scrutiny. <em>Tishmor</em> (to keep, guard, watch, preserve — the same word as Ps 121\'s "keeper"): if YHWH "kept" sins the way a good keeper guards what is entrusted to him, the record would be complete and damning. "Who could stand?" — the legal standing question: the courtroom in which no human being could stand without being condemned immediately. The argument from impossible human righteousness to the necessity of divine forgiveness is the OT\'s most direct anticipation of Paul\'s argument in Romans 3: "all have sinned and fall short of the glory of God" (Rom 3:23) requires the divine solution of justification through Christ (Rom 3:24).</p>',
    "4": '<p>"But forgiveness is found with you (<em>ki-immekha hasselikhah</em>) — and that is why you are held in awe (<em>lemaan tivvare</em>)" — one of the most paradoxical statements in the Psalter: it is divine forgiveness (not divine wrath) that produces reverential awe. The logic: if YHWH simply maintained the strict record of sins and punished accordingly, the response would be dread-fear, not reverent awe — and humans would flee from the divine presence rather than seek it. It is precisely because YHWH forgives that the covenant community dares to approach, and approaching, discovers the awe of the divine holiness. <em>Selichah</em> (forgiveness, pardon, the release of the debt) appears only three times in the OT (here; Dan 9:9; Neh 9:17) — always in combination with divine character declarations. The rarity makes its occurrence here emphatic: this is the specific divine attribute being claimed as the basis for prayer.</p>',
    "5": '<p>"I wait for the LORD (<em>qivviti YHWH</em>) — my whole being waits — and in his word I put my hope (<em>lidevaro hohhalti</em>)" — the posture of waiting (<em>qavah</em>, to wait with expectation, to hope, to be stretched taut like a bow-string toward the anticipated arrival) is not passive resignation but active, oriented anticipation. "My whole being waits" — the <em>nefesh</em> (inner person, the totality of self) engaged in the waiting: the entire person is oriented toward YHWH\'s response. "In his word (<em>devaro</em>)" — the ground of the hope is not general optimism but the specific divine promise: the "word" that YHWH has spoken and that has not yet been fulfilled in the psalmist\'s experience. The hope is anchored in the covenant word, not in the psalmist\'s own assessment of the situation.</p>',
    "6": '<p>"My soul waits for the Lord more than sentinels long for the morning light (<em>shomrim laboker</em>) — yes, more than sentinels wait for morning" — the night watchman on the city wall, standing guard through the darkness and counting the hours until the relief of dawn, is the image of sustained, alert, expectant hope. The sentinel does not sleep — he waits actively, scanning the horizon for the first light of dawn. The repetition "more than sentinels wait for morning... more than sentinels wait for morning" (the phrase occurs twice) functions as staircase parallelism: the second occurrence intensifies and confirms the first. The dawn that the sentinel awaits is inevitable — it will come regardless of how long the night has been. The psalmist\'s hope in YHWH\'s response is described with that same inevitability: the morning <em>will</em> come.</p>',
    "7": '<p>"O Israel, put your hope in the LORD (<em>yahhel Yisra\'el el-YHWH</em>), for with the LORD is steadfast love (<em>hesed</em>), and with him is abundant redemption (<em>harbeh immo fedut</em>)" — the movement from individual petition (vv. 1-6) to corporate exhortation (vv. 7-8): the individual\'s experience of the depths and the waiting becomes the basis for calling the whole community to the same hope. "With the LORD is <em>hesed</em>" — covenant loyalty, steadfast love, the committed faithfulness of the covenanting God. "<em>Harbeh</em> redemption" (abundant, much, plentiful redemption) — not a scant or barely sufficient redemption but a redemption that exceeds the measure of what needs redeeming. <em>Pedut</em> (redemption, the deliverance that pays the full price) — the ransom-type word that the NT will take up in the theology of Christ as the one who "gave himself as a ransom for many" (Mark 10:45).</p>',
    "8": '<p>"He will redeem Israel from all its sins (<em>yifdeh et-Yisra\'el mikkol avonotav</em>)" — the psalm closes with the most comprehensive statement: the redemption YHWH offers is total ("from <em>all</em> its sins") and corporate (the entire people). The individual De Profundis prayer, which began in the most personal, isolated experience of depth (v1: "I cry out"), ends with a universal covenant promise covering all of Israel\'s sins. The individual is carried into the corporate promise; the corporate redemption is experienced by the individual in prayer. The NT will read this verse through the lens of Christ\'s atoning work: 1 John 1:7 ("the blood of Jesus, his Son, purifies us from all sin") and Rom 11:26 ("all Israel will be saved") both expand the scope of Ps 130:8\'s promise through the mechanism of the cross.</p>',
  },
  "131": {
    "1": '<p>Psalm 131, attributed to David, is one of the shortest psalms in the Psalter and perhaps the most concentrated in its spiritual achievement. It models the inner posture that the entire Songs of Ascents collection is designed to produce. "LORD, my heart is not proud (<em>lo-gavah libbi</em>); my eyes are not raised in arrogance (<em>ve\'lo-ramu einai</em>); I do not involve myself with matters too great or too wonderful (<em>beniflaut</em>) for me" — the three negations define humility through its opposite: pride of heart (the inner disposition), elevated eyes (the visible arrogance posture), and involvement in matters beyond one\'s proper sphere. The "matters too wonderful (<em>niflaut</em>)" may refer to divine mysteries, cosmic decisions, or the political and theological questions that belong to YHWH rather than to human calculation. The humble person recognizes the sphere of human competence and remains within it.</p>',
    "2": '<p>"No, I have settled and silenced my soul (<em>shivviti ve\'domamti nafshi</em>); like a weaned child (<em>kegamul</em>) resting contentedly with its mother — like a weaned child, my soul is with me" — the weaned child image is the psalm\'s center and requires careful reading. The <em>gamul</em> (weaned child, one who has been weaned) is specifically not the nursing infant who cries for milk — it is the child who has already passed through the weaning crisis (which in antiquity occurred around ages 2-3, when the child was abruptly separated from the breast) and arrived at a settled contentment without demanding to nurse. This is not passivity or infant dependency but achieved tranquility: the child has worked through the crisis of being denied what it most wanted and found peace on the other side. The psalmist has done the same: the soul (<em>nefesh</em>) that once cried out demanding divine answers has been weaned and now rests quietly — not in ignorance but in trust.</p>',
    "3": '<p>"O Israel, put your hope in the LORD both now and forever (<em>me\'attah ve\'ad-olam</em>)" — the tiny psalm closes with the same corporate exhortation as Ps 130:7 ("O Israel, put your hope in the LORD") and with the same temporal formula as Ps 121:8 ("now and forever"). The individual achievement of the weaned-child tranquility (v2) becomes the model for the corporate community\'s hope. What the psalmist has personally achieved — the silencing and settling of the demanding soul — is offered to the whole covenant community as the goal of the pilgrimage journey. The Songs of Ascents that began with the cry of distress in "Meshech and Kedar" (Ps 120:5) have traveled through fear, arrival, petition, thanksgiving, and penitential depth to arrive here: the settled, trusting soul that rests in YHWH without demands. Israel is called to this same achieved peace.</p>',
  },
  "132": {
    "1": '<p>Psalm 132 is the Davidic covenant psalm at the heart of the Songs of Ascents — the longest and most theologically weighty of the collection. It is divided into two matched sections: vv. 1-10 (the human initiative of David\'s oath) and vv. 11-18 (the divine counter-oath of the Davidic covenant). 2 Chr 6:41-42 quotes vv. 8-10 directly in Solomon\'s temple dedication prayer, confirming that this psalm was the liturgical script for that event. "O LORD, remember David (<em>zekor-David</em>) — remember all his hardships (<em>umiso annoto</em>)" — the petition for divine memory is covenantal action: YHWH "remembers" the covenant by acting on it (Gen 9:15; Exod 2:24; 6:5; Lev 26:42; Ps 105:8; 106:45). To ask YHWH to "remember David" is to ask him to act on the Davidic covenant. "All his hardships (<em>umiso</em>)" — the afflictions David endured in the process of bringing the ark to Jerusalem: the rejected attempt (2 Sam 6:1-11), the death of Uzzah, the three-month delay, and the final successful procession.</p>',
    "2": '<p>"How he made a solemn oath (<em>nishba</em>) to the LORD and vowed (<em>nadar</em>) to the Mighty One of Jacob (<em>Avir Yaakov</em>)" — the double covenant formula: oath and vow together constitute the most binding form of human commitment available in the OT. <em>Avir Yaakov</em> (the Mighty One of Jacob) is an archaic divine title (Gen 49:24; Isa 1:24; 49:26; 60:16; Ps 132:5) connected to the patriarchal tradition and the covenant with Jacob. The use of this archaic title in a royal psalm connects the Davidic covenant to the much earlier patriarchal covenant: David\'s oath is placed within the larger framework of the covenant that goes back to Abraham, Isaac, and Jacob.</p>',
    "3": '<p>"\'I will not enter my house, nor climb into my bed\'" — David\'s vow is quoted directly (vv. 3-5) as a commitment to deny himself normal household comforts until he finds a permanent home for the ark of YHWH. The self-denial of household rest (not entering the house, not lying in the bed) for the sake of securing divine rest (a dwelling for YHWH) is the inversion of royal comfort: the king who should be served first instead makes himself serve YHWH first. The ark of the covenant was housed in various temporary locations after the Philistines returned it: Kiriath-jearim (1 Sam 7:1-2), then Obed-edom\'s house (2 Sam 6:10-12), before David brought it to Jerusalem. David\'s distress over the ark\'s lack of a permanent home (2 Sam 7:2: "I am living in a house of cedar, while the ark of God remains in a tent") is the background of the vow.</p>',
    "4": '<p>"\'I will allow no sleep to my eyes, no slumber to my eyelids\'" — the second element of David\'s vow: no sleep until the task is accomplished. The "no sleep, no slumber" formula echoes Ps 121:3-4\'s description of YHWH ("he who keeps you will not slumber... will not slumber or sleep") — creating a deliberate parallel: the king who refuses sleep to find a dwelling for YHWH mirrors the God who refuses sleep to keep his people. The servant who stays awake to serve the divine king takes on a character trait of the king himself. David\'s wakeful devotion to finding a place for YHWH becomes a template for the community\'s devotion: the pilgrimage itself is an act of seeking the divine dwelling-place that David sought.</p>',
    "5": '<p>"\'Until I find a fitting place (<em>maqom</em>) for the LORD — a dwelling (<em>mishkan</em>) for the Mighty One of Jacob\'" — the vocabulary is deliberate: <em>maqom</em> (place) is the standard term for sacred sites in the OT (Gen 12:6; 22:4; 28:11, 17, 19); <em>mishkan</em> (dwelling, tabernacle) is the term for the wilderness Tabernacle (Exod 25:9; 26:1; etc.). David seeks a permanent place that will replace the temporary wilderness Tabernacle. The "dwelling for the Mighty One of Jacob" — the ark of the covenant was YHWH\'s footstool-throne (Ps 99:5; 1 Chr 28:2); finding a place for the ark was finding a place for YHWH to "rest" (v8, <em>menuhatecha</em>) after the long journey through the wilderness. The theme of divine rest (<em>nuah</em>) runs from the Sabbath (Gen 2:2-3) through the wilderness wandering to the temple (1 Kgs 8:56-57; Ps 132:14).</p>',
    "6": '<p>"We heard of the ark at Ephrathah (<em>Efratah</em>); we discovered it in the fields of Jaar (<em>sedeh-yaar</em>)" — Ephrathah is Bethlehem (Gen 35:19; 48:7; Ruth 4:11; 1 Sam 17:12; Mic 5:2), David\'s hometown; the "fields of Jaar" is Kiriath-jearim ("city of forests/Jaar"), where the ark was kept at the house of Abinadab for twenty years after the Philistines returned it (1 Sam 6:21-7:2; 2 Sam 6:2). The community that "heard of" the ark in Bethlehem (where David grew up with knowledge of the ark\'s location) and "found it" at Kiriath-jearim recalls the generational journey from hearing to finding — the theological movement from transmitted tradition to experiential encounter. The pilgrimage to Jerusalem re-enacts this discovery journey.</p>',
    "7": '<p>"Let us go to his dwelling place (<em>mishkenotav</em>); let us bow down (<em>nishtahaveh</em>) at his footstool (<em>lahadom raglav</em>)" — the call to pilgrimage and worship at the ark-throne. The ark between the cherubim was the divine footstool (1 Chr 28:2; Ps 99:5) — the place where the King of heaven condescended to be accessible to the covenant community. "Let us bow down" (<em>shahhah</em>, to prostrate, to bow in submission and worship) — the full-body prostration before the enthroned king. The pilgrimage destination (Jerusalem, the temple) is the place where one bows before the footstool of the divine king; the physical act of prostration in pilgrimage worship is the bodily enactment of the covenant submission that the entire Songs of Ascents collection describes.</p>',
    "8": '<p>"Rise up, O LORD, to your resting place (<em>menuhatecha</em>) — you and the ark that holds your power (<em>aron uzzecha</em>)" — the ark-procession prayer that 2 Chr 6:41 places directly in Solomon\'s mouth at the temple dedication. The "rise up, O LORD" formula echoes Num 10:35 (the wilderness ark-procession cry: "Arise, LORD! May your enemies be scattered...") — connecting Solomon\'s temple dedication to the wilderness journeying of the ark. "Your resting place" (<em>menuhatecha</em>) — the destination of the ark\'s long journey: from Sinai through the wilderness, through the period of the judges, through the Philistine captivity, through Kiriath-jearim, to the tent David pitched for it in Jerusalem, and now to the permanent temple. The ark "holds your power" (<em>aron uzzecha</em>, the ark of your strength) — the covenant presence-power of YHWH travels with and is somehow associated with the ark.</p>',
    "9": '<p>"Clothe your priests with righteousness (<em>tzedek</em>), and let your devoted people (<em>hasidecha</em>) shout for joy" — the two recipient groups of the divine blessing at the temple dedication: the priests (who serve at the altar) and the <em>hasidim</em> (the covenant-faithful community). Priests "clothed with righteousness" — the priestly vestments (Exod 28:1-43) had a theological significance: the robes were the visible expression of the holiness required for approach to the divine presence. But this verse asks for something more than the physical garments: righteous character (<em>tzedek</em>) as the clothing that counts. The parallel in 2 Chr 6:41 is identical, confirming that this verse was central to the temple-dedication liturgy and became the standard prayer for priestly character throughout the Second Temple period.</p>',
    "10": '<p>"For your servant David\'s sake, do not reject (<em>al-tashev</em>) your anointed king (<em>mishiheka</em>)" — the petition that links David\'s oath (vv. 1-5) to the divine response (vv. 11-18): because David kept his covenant commitment to YHWH, YHWH should maintain his covenant commitment to the Davidic line. The anointed king (<em>mashiach</em>) is both the currently reigning Davidic king and, in the trajectory of the Psalter, the ultimate Davidic heir who will not be rejected. Ps 89:38-45 presents the apparent rejection of the anointed as the community\'s most pressing theological crisis; Ps 132:10 preemptively petitions against that rejection on the basis of David\'s faithfulness. The NT reads "your anointed" as fulfilled ultimately in Jesus (Acts 4:26-27; Luke 2:11, 26).</p>',
    "11": '<p>"The LORD made a sworn, true covenant (<em>nishba YHWH leDavid emet</em>) with David — he will never go back on it (<em>lo yashuv mimmenah</em>): \'I will place one of your own descendants on your throne (<em>mipri vitnecha ashit lekise-lach</em>)\'" — the divine counter-oath matches David\'s oath (vv. 2-5). David swore and vowed (v2); YHWH swore in truth (<em>emet</em>, faithfulness, reliability). The promise quotes the Davidic covenant of 2 Sam 7:12-13: "I will raise up your offspring to succeed you... I will establish his kingdom." "He will never go back on it (<em>lo yashuv mimmenah</em>)" — the irrevocability of the divine oath; unlike human oaths that can be broken, YHWH\'s sworn word stands regardless of circumstances. Ps 89:3-4 celebrates this same sworn covenant; the NT reads the irrevocability of the divine oath through Christ as the guarantor of the new covenant (Heb 6:17-18; 7:20-22).</p>',
    "12": '<p>"\'If your sons keep my covenant and the decrees I teach them, their sons too shall sit upon your throne forever\'" — the conditional clause distinguishes two levels of the Davidic covenant: the unconditional promise that a Davidic heir will sit on the throne, and the conditional promise that the particular sons of David will occupy the throne if they keep the covenant. The failure of specific Davidic kings (the sin of Solomon, the apostasy of Manasseh) did not nullify the covenant promise but meant that those particular kings forfeited their personal participation in the promise. The unconditional element — that the Davidic line would have an heir on the throne — pointed forward to the one whose covenant-keeping would be perfect: the NT reads this as fulfilled in Christ, who keeps the covenant perfectly and whose rule on the throne is therefore unconditional and eternal (Luke 1:32-33; Acts 2:30-31).</p>',
    "13": '<p>"The LORD has chosen Zion (<em>bahar YHWH beTziyyon</em>); he has made it his desired home (<em>ivo lemoshav lo</em>)" — the divine election of Zion: YHWH\'s choice is the foundation of Zion\'s theological significance. The choice is not based on Zion\'s inherent qualities (the hill is not large or particularly strategic by ancient Near Eastern standards) but on the divine desire (<em>avah</em>, to desire, to long for). "He has made it his desired home" — the divine desire for a specific dwelling place among his people is the covenant condescension: the creator of heaven and earth chooses a particular mountain on earth as his address, making himself accessible at a specific location. This is the OT\'s most direct statement of the theology of incarnation by anticipation: YHWH desires to dwell with his people in a specific, locatable place.</p>',
    "14": '<p>"\'This is my resting place forever (<em>zot menuhat-li ad-olam</em>); here I will live, for I have longed for it (<em>po eshev ki ividtiha</em>)\'" — the divine resting is the completion of the long ark-journey and the cosmic pattern of the Sabbath rest (Gen 2:2-3). YHWH\'s declaration "here I will live" (<em>po eshev</em>) is the theological climax of the entire psalm and of the ark-theology: the divine presence that has been mobile (wilderness tabernacle, the period of the judges, the long journey to Jerusalem) now declares a permanent dwelling. "For I have longed for it (<em>avah</em>)" — the same word used in v13 for YHWH\'s desire for Zion: the divine desire has found its satisfaction in the permanent rest at Zion. The NT\'s "the Word became flesh and tabernacled among us" (John 1:14) is the fulfillment of this desire at the deepest possible level.</p>',
    "15": '<p>"\'I will richly bless her food supply (<em>tzidah barek avarak</em>); I will fill the poor with bread (<em>evyoneha ashbia lehem</em>)\'" — the material blessings of YHWH\'s dwelling at Zion: the divine presence at Jerusalem is productive for the poor. "Rich blessing" (<em>barek avarak</em>, the doubled infinitive absolute for intensity: "I will bless, yes bless") — the emphatic divine commitment to Zion\'s provision. The poor (<em>evyonim</em>) specifically receive the bread: the divine dwelling at Zion is not merely a royal or priestly benefit but extends to the marginalized. Jesus\'s feeding miracles, where he "blessed" the bread and the crowd ate until full (Matt 14:19-21; 15:36-38), activate this promise in their form and vocabulary — the presence of the true temple (John 2:19-21) produces the feeding of the poor at Zion.</p>',
    "16": '<p>"\'I will dress her priests with salvation (<em>kohaneiha albishe yeshua</em>), and her devoted people will shout with joy (<em>hasideha ranen yerannenu</em>)\'" — salvation (<em>yeshua</em>) as priestly vestment: the counterpart to v9\'s request for "righteousness" as priestly clothing. Here it is YHWH himself who clothes the priests with salvation — not human righteousness but divine salvation as the garment of the priestly ministry. The verbal connection between <em>yeshua</em> (salvation) and the name <em>Yeshua</em> (Jesus) is not merely etymological: the NT presents Jesus as the high priest who is himself clothed with salvation and who is salvation (Heb 5:5-6; 7:26-28; John 14:6). The <em>hasidim</em> who "shout with joy" are the covenant-loyal community whose joy in YHWH\'s salvation is the doxological response to the dwelling of divine salvation at Zion.</p>',
    "17": '<p>"\'There I will make a shoot of strength grow for David (<em>atzamih qeren leDavid</em>); I have set a lamp ready (<em>arakti ner</em>) for my anointed\'" — two royal images for the Davidic heir: the horn of strength (<em>qeren</em>) and the lamp (<em>ner</em>). The horn of strength (animal horn as the symbol of power — Ps 75:4-5; 89:17, 24; 92:10; 148:14; Dan 7:7-8; Zech 1:18-21) is the royal power of the Davidic king who will be raised up from Zion. The lamp is the image of perpetual dynasty in the covenant promise to David (1 Kgs 11:36: "I will give one tribe to his son so that David my servant may always have a lamp before me in Jerusalem"; 15:4; 2 Kgs 8:19); the lamp that is never extinguished is the dynasty that does not end. Luke 1:69 applies the horn-of-strength image directly to Jesus: "he has raised up a horn of salvation for us in the house of his servant David."</p>',
    "18": '<p>"\'I will dress his enemies in shame (<em>oyvav albishe boshet</em>), but his crown (<em>nizro</em>) will gleam (<em>yatzitz</em>) upon his head\'" — the final contrasting image: the enemies who opposed the Davidic covenant receive shame (<em>boshet</em>) as their clothing — the inverse of the salvation-garment of v16 — while the anointed king\'s crown shines brilliantly. <em>Yatzitz</em> (to gleam, to blossom, to shine forth) — the crown that blossoms with radiance; the same verb is used of the blossoming of flowers (Isa 27:6; 35:1-2) and of the spreading of divine glory. The gleaming crown of the Davidic anointed king is the culminating image of the entire psalm: from David\'s nightless search for a home for the ark to YHWH\'s dwelling at Zion to the gleaming crown of the anointed — a trajectory that the NT reads as pointing to the crown of thorns transformed into the crown of glory (Phil 2:8-9; Rev 19:12).</p>',
  },
  "133": {
    "1": '<p>Psalm 133, attributed to David, is one of the Songs of Ascents and one of the most concentrated poems in the Psalter — three verses that explore the beauty of covenant brotherhood. "How wonderfully good (<em>mah-tov umah-naim</em>) it is, how delightful, when brothers (<em>ahim</em>) live together as one (<em>yashev yahdav</em>)!" — the exclamation of aesthetic pleasure in communal covenant unity. <em>Tov</em> (good) and <em>naim</em> (pleasant, delightful, sweet) are wisdom-aesthetic judgments: this is not merely a moral evaluation but a claim about the beauty of covenant community life. "Brothers living together as one" — <em>yahdav</em> (together, as a unity): the kinship language of "brothers" encompasses the covenant community that is constituted as a family by its shared relationship to the one God. The pilgrimage festivals created exactly this — the scattered tribal communities gathered together in one place, living as brothers for the duration of the feast.</p>',
    "2": '<p>"It is like costly anointing oil poured on the head (<em>rosh</em>), running down over the beard — Aaron\'s beard — flowing all the way down to the collar of his robes (<em>pi middotav</em>)" — the anointing oil of the high priest: the sacred anointing oil (<em>shemen hammishha</em>) of Exod 30:22-33 — myrrh, cinnamon, cassia, and olive oil — was used exclusively for consecrating the high priest and the sanctuary furnishings (Exod 30:26-32). Its application to Aaron (Lev 8:12: "Moses poured some of the anointing oil on Aaron\'s head and anointed him") was the act of priestly consecration, the setting apart of the person for divine service. The oil flowing generously from head to beard to collar represents the full, excessive anointing — nothing held back. The image for brotherhood: the unity of brothers at Zion is like being caught up in the excess of consecrating oil, like being part of the priestly community where the Spirit\'s presence flows without measure.</p>',
    "3": '<p>"It is like the dew of Hermon (<em>tal-hermon</em>) descending on the mountains of Zion — for there the LORD has commanded the blessing: life to the age (<em>hayyim ad-haolam</em>)" — Mount Hermon (2,814m, the highest peak in the region) collects moisture from the Mediterranean that falls as extraordinarily heavy dew; it is one of the wettest points in the entire Levant. The image of Hermon\'s dew descending on Zion\'s mountains (much lower, much drier) is deliberately abundant and generous — it would require a different weather system from what actually occurs, but the hyperbole makes the theological point: the blessing of fraternal unity at Zion is like receiving Hermon-level abundance in a Zion-level environment. "There the LORD has commanded the blessing" — the divine command (<em>tzivvah</em>) is what causes the blessing to flow; it is not a natural phenomenon but a covenant act. "Life to the age (<em>hayyim ad-haolam</em>)" — the eschatological telos: fraternal unity at Zion is the foretaste of the eternal life that belongs to the coming age, the life that the covenant community will know fully when the divine dwelling is complete (Rev 21:22-22:5).</p>',
  },
}

def main():
    existing = load_comm('mkt-context', 'psalms')
    merge_comm(existing, PSALMS)
    save_comm('mkt-context', 'psalms', existing)
    print('Psalms 120-133 mkt-context written.')

if __name__ == '__main__':
    main()
